==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Swoon
<hw>Swoon</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Swooned</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Swooning</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>swounen</ets>,
<ets>swoghenen</ets>, for <ets>swo<?/nien</ets>, fr. <ets>swo<?/en</ets>
to sigh deeply, to droop, AS. <ets>sw⟦omac⟧gan</ets> to sough, sigh; cf.
ge<ets>sw⟦omac⟧gen</ets> senseless, swooned, ge<ets>sw⟦omac⟧wung</ets> a
swooning. Cf. <er>Sough</er>.]</ety> <def>To sink into a fainting fit,
in which there is an apparent suspension of the vital functions and
mental powers; to faint; -- often with <xex>away</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The sucklings <qex>swoon</qex> in the streets of the city.</q>
<rj><qau>Lam. ii. 11.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The most in years . . . <qex>swooned</qex> first away for
pain.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He seemed ready to <qex>swoon</qex> away in the surprise of
joy.</q> <rj><qau>Tatler.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Swoon</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Swoon
<hw>Swoon</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A fainting fit; syncope.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Swooning</ent>⟦br⟧
